  "prompt": "What is frictional force?",
  "response": "Frictional force is a force that resists the relative motion of surfaces in contact with each other. Here are key points about friction:\n\n1. Definition\n- A force that opposes the motion of one surface sliding or attempting to slide over another surface\n\n2. Types of Friction\n- Static friction: Prevents objects from starting to move\n- Kinetic friction: Occurs when objects are already in motion\n- Rolling friction: Resistance experienced by rolling objects\n\n3. Factors Affecting Friction\n- Nature of surfaces (roughness)\n- Force pressing surfaces together\n- Weight of the object\n- Material of the surfaces\n\n4. Direction\n- Always acts opposite to the direction of motion or potential motion\n- Parallel to the contact surface\n\n5. Calculation\n- Friction force = Coefficient of friction \u00d7 Normal force\n\n6. Effects\n- Helps in walking\n- Allows vehicles to move\n- Causes energy loss in mechanical systems\n- Generates heat\n\n7. Applications\n- Braking systems\n- Grip and traction\n- Holding objects in place\n\n8. Can be both helpful and harmful depending on the context\n\nFriction is an essential physical phenomenon that plays a crucial role in many everyday and technological processes.",
